<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-week-02">
  <title>Week 2</title>

  <subsection>
    <title>Monday</title>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Topology from the categorical viewpoint</title>
        <aside>
          <p>
            One of my favorite math books is John Milnor's <pubtitle>Topology from the differentiable viewpoint</pubtitle>, 
            which serves as inspiration for the the section title here.
          </p>
        </aside>

  <p>
    One of the primary insights of twentieth century mathematics is that <alert>objects</alert> should not be studied in
    isolation. Rather, to understand objects we must also understand <alert>relationships</alert> between objects.
    Topologies offer one notion of “relation”, organizing the points of a set into neighborhoods. As an abstraction
    of geometry, topology is immensely successful, but it fails to capture a second, more structural notion of relation.
  </p>

  <p>
    <alert>Category theory</alert> organizes objects by their transformations. Once these notions of object and relation are
    abstracted, it becomes possible to compare and contrast different fields of mathematics. Theorems about wildly
    different mathematical objects are often identical in their categorical content. In this manner, category theory
    becomes a meta-mathematical tool for both identifying and conjecturing structural results.
  </p>

  <p>
    Our present goal is to use the 
    language of category theory to motivate definitions and interpret theorems. Moving into the algebro-topological portion of the course,
    this language will become even more important as we use the homology <term>functor</term> to compare the
    categories of topological spaces and vector spaces.
  </p>
</subsubsection>

  <subsubsection xml:id="sec-categories">
    <title>Categories</title>

    <p>
      We begin with a motivating example. Sets are a type of mathematical object. Sets are related by functions.
      Each function has a domain (source) and codomain (target). In standard notation, <m>f:A\to B</m> denotes
      a function with domain <m>A</m> and codomain <m>B</m>. Of course, functions admit composition: given
      <m>g:B\to C</m> and <m>f:A\to B</m> we can form <m>g\circ f:A\to C</m> by assigning <m>g(f(a))</m> to
      <m>a\in A</m>. This composition is associative: if <m>f:A\to B</m>, <m>g:B\to C</m>, and <m>h:C\to D</m>
      are functions, then
      <md>h\circ(g\circ f) = (h\circ g)\circ f.</md>
    </p>

    <p>
      Moreover, each set (even the empty set!) admits an identity function <m>\operatorname{id}_A:A\to A</m>. This function takes
      each <m>a\in A</m> to <m>a</m> and satisfies the following property: for each <m>g:A\to B</m> and each
      <m>f:C\to A</m>,
    </p>

    <p>
      <md>g\circ \operatorname{id}_A = g\qquad\text{and}\qquad \operatorname{id}_A\circ f = f.</md>
    </p>

    <p>
      In the following definition, we will see that categories consist of objects, morphisms (with source and target
      objects), composition, and identity morphisms satisfying associativity and identity properties. As such, sets and
      functions form our first example of a category.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-category">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>category</term> <m>\mathcal{C}</m> consists of a collection of <term>objects</term> <m>\mathrm{Ob}\,\mathcal{C}</m>
          and a collection of <term>morphisms</term> <m>\mathrm{Mor}\,\mathcal{C}</m> along with assignments
          <m>s,t:\mathrm{Mor}\,\mathcal{C}\to \mathrm{Ob}\,\mathcal{C}</m> (called the <term>source</term> and <term>target</term> maps).
          Let <m>\mathcal{C}(x,y)\subseteq \mathrm{Mor}\,\mathcal{C}</m> denote the collection of morphisms with source
          <m>x\in \mathrm{Ob}\,\mathcal{C}</m> and target <m>y\in \mathrm{Ob}\,\mathcal{C}</m>. Then for each
          <m>x,y,z\in \mathrm{Ob}\,\mathcal{C}</m>, <m>\mathcal{C}</m> is also equipped with a <term>composition</term>
          <md>
            <mrow>\circ\colon \mathcal{C}(y,z)\times \mathcal{C}(x,y) \amp \longrightarrow \mathcal{C}(x,z)</mrow>
            <mrow>(g,f) \amp \longmapsto g\circ f.</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          Additionally, for each <m>x\in \mathrm{Ob}\,\mathcal{C}</m> there is an <term>identity morphism</term>
          <m>\operatorname{id}_x\in \mathcal{C}(x,x)</m>. This data must satisfy the following properties:
        </p>

        <dl>
         <li>
           <title>Associativity:</title>
           <p>
             For objects <m>x,y,z,w</m> and morphisms <m>f\in \mathcal{C}(x,y)</m>,
             <m>g\in \mathcal{C}(y,z)</m>, and <m>h\in \mathcal{C}(z,w)</m>, we have
             <md>h\circ(g\circ f) = (h\circ g)\circ f.</md>
           </p>
         </li>
       
         <li>
            <title>Identity:</title>
            <p>
              For each <m>x,y\in \mathrm{Ob}\,\mathcal{C}</m>, <m>f\in \mathcal{C}(x,y)</m>, and
              <m>g\in \mathcal{C}(y,x)</m>, we have
              <md>f\circ \operatorname{id}_x = f\qquad\text{and}\qquad \operatorname{id}_x\circ g = g.</md>
            </p>
          </li>
        </dl>

      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      It is useful to think about categories diagrammatically. These diagrams use letters to represent objects, and
      labelled arrows to represent morphisms. So if <m>x,y\in \mathrm{Ob}\,\mathcal{C}</m> and <m>f\in \mathcal{C}(x,y)</m>,
      we may draw an arrow from <m>x</m> to <m>y</m> labelled <m>f</m> in order to represent that <m>f</m> is a morphism
      with source <m>x</m> and target <m>y</m>. (Note that we have dropped <m>\mathcal{C}</m> from our notation here:
      usually it will be clear from context which category we are working in.) We may also write <m>f\colon x\to y</m> to
      represent <m>f\in \mathcal{C}(x,y)</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Now suppose that in addition to <m>f</m> we also have a morphism <m>g\colon y\to z</m>. Composition tells us that we then
      get a new morphism <m>g\circ f\colon x\to z</m>. We can put all of this information into a single <em>commutative diagram</em>.
    </p>
      <image width="55%">
        <prefigure label="comm-triangle" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
          <diagram dimensions="(320,230)" margins="5">
            <coordinates bbox="(-1.35,-0.2,1.35,1.45)">

              <definition>graph={0:[1,2], 1:[2]}</definition>

              <network directed="yes" arrows="end"
                       graph="graph"
                       labels="yes"
                       node-style="circle"
                       node-fill="white" node-stroke="none"
                       node-size="30">

                <node at="0" p="(-1,0)"><m>x</m></node>
                <node at="1" p="(0,1.1)"><m>y</m></node>
                <node at="2" p="(1,0)"><m>z</m></node>

                <edge vertices="(0,1)" label-location="0.50" alignment="nw"><m>f</m></edge>
                <edge vertices="(1,2)" label-location="0.50" alignment="ne"><m>g</m></edge>
                <edge vertices="(0,2)" label-location="0.50" alignment="south"><m>g\circ f</m></edge>

              </network>
            </coordinates>
          </diagram>
        </prefigure>
        <description>
          A triangle with objects <m>x</m>, <m>y</m>, <m>z</m> and arrows <m>f\colon x\to y</m>, <m>g\colon y\to z</m>, 
          and <m>g\circ f\colon x\to z</m>. The arrows form a triangle with indicated sources and targets.
        </description>
      </image>0
    <p>
      When we say that a diagram like the one above <alert>commutes</alert>, we are saying precisely that the two paths from
      <m>x</m> to <m>z</m> determine the same morphism, i.e. the bottom arrow equals the composite of the two slanted arrows.
      The geometric presentation of the diagram is unimportant; we can rearrange the nodes without changing the meaning.
    </p>

    <p>
      We can also use diagrams to express the axioms for a category. Associativity can be pictured as the statement that
      two different ways of composing <m>f</m>, <m>g</m>, and <m>h</m> agree.
    </p>
      <image width="70%">
        <prefigure label="assoc-diagram" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
          <diagram dimensions="(460,240)" margins="5">
            <coordinates bbox="(-1.6,-0.2,1.6,1.25)">

              <definition>graph={0:[1,2], 1:[2,3], 2:[3]}</definition>

              <network directed="yes" arrows="end"
                       graph="graph"
                       labels="yes"
                       node-style="circle"
                       node-fill="white" node-stroke="none"
                       node-size="30">

                <!-- nodes: 0=x, 1=y, 2=z, 3=w -->
                <node at="0" p="(-1.35,0)"><m>x</m></node>
                <node at="1" p="(-0.35,1.0)"><m>y</m></node>
                <node at="2" p="(0.55,0)"><m>z</m></node>
                <node at="3" p="(1.35,1.0)"><m>w</m></node>

                <!-- basic arrows -->
                <edge vertices="(0,1)" label-location="0.50" alignment="nw"><m>f</m></edge>
                <edge vertices="(1,2)" label-location="0.50" alignment="ne"><m>g</m></edge>
                <edge vertices="(2,3)" label-location="0.50" alignment="se"><m>h</m></edge>

                <!-- composites displayed as additional arrows -->
                <edge vertices="(0,2)" label-location="0.50" alignment="south"><m>g\circ f</m></edge>
                <edge vertices="(1,3)" label-location="0.50" alignment="north"><m>h\circ g</m></edge>

              </network>
            </coordinates>
          </diagram>
        </prefigure>
        <description>
          A four-object diagram showing arrows <m>f</m>, <m>g</m>, <m>h</m> and the composites <m>g\circ f</m>, <m>h\circ g</m>.
        </description>
      </image>

    <p>
      We can interpret this axiom as saying that we can paste together commutative triangles to produce commutative quadrilaterals.
      The identity axiom also admits a simple diagrammatic expression.
    </p>


      <sidebyside widths="45% 45%" valign="middle">
        <image>
          <prefigure label="id-left" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
            <diagram dimensions="(320,240)" margins="5">
              <coordinates bbox="(-1.35,-0.2,1.35,1.35)">

                <definition>graph={0:[1,2], 1:[2]}</definition>

                <network directed="yes" arrows="end"
                         graph="graph"
                         labels="yes"
                         node-style="circle"
                         node-fill="white" node-stroke="none"
                         node-size="30">

                  <!-- 0 = x (left), 1 = x (top-right), 2 = y (bottom-right) -->
                  <node at="0" p="(-1,0.2)"><m>x</m></node>
                  <node at="1" p="(0.8,1.1)"><m>x</m></node>
                  <node at="2" p="(0.8,0.0)"><m>y</m></node>

                  <edge vertices="(0,1)" label-location="0.50" alignment="nw"><m>\operatorname{id}_x</m></edge>
                  <edge vertices="(1,2)" label-location="0.50" alignment="e"><m>f</m></edge>
                  <edge vertices="(0,2)" label-location="0.50" alignment="south"><m>f</m></edge>

                </network>
              </coordinates>
            </diagram>
          </prefigure>
          <description>
            A triangle expressing <m>f\circ \operatorname{id}_x=f</m>.
          </description>
        </image>

        <image>
          <prefigure label="id-right" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
            <diagram dimensions="(320,240)" margins="5">
              <coordinates bbox="(-1.35,-0.2,1.35,1.35)">

                <definition>graph={0:[1,2], 1:[2]}</definition>

                <network directed="yes" arrows="end"
                         graph="graph"
                         labels="yes"
                         node-style="circle"
                         node-fill="white" node-stroke="none"
                         node-size="30">

                  <!-- 0 = y (left), 1 = x (top-right), 2 = x (bottom-right) -->
                  <node at="0" p="(-1,0.2)"><m>y</m></node>
                  <node at="1" p="(0.8,1.1)"><m>x</m></node>
                  <node at="2" p="(0.8,0.0)"><m>x</m></node>

                  <edge vertices="(0,1)" label-location="0.50" alignment="nw"><m>g</m></edge>
                  <edge vertices="(1,2)" label-location="0.50" alignment="e"><m>\operatorname{id}_x</m></edge>
                  <edge vertices="(0,2)" label-location="0.50" alignment="south"><m>g</m></edge>

                </network>
              </coordinates>
            </diagram>
          </prefigure>
          <description>
            A triangle expressing <m>\operatorname{id}_x\circ g=g</m>.
          </description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>

    <p>
      Without realizing it, you have been working with categories for a long time. Consider the following examples.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="eg-sets">
      <title>The category of sets and functions</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          We have already mentioned that sets and functions form a category. We denote this category <m>\mathsf{Set}</m>.
          Similarly, there is a category <m>\mathsf{FinSet}</m> with objects finite sets and morphisms functions between finite sets.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-vect">
      <title>The category of vector spaces and linear transformations</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>k</m> be a field and let <m>\mathsf{Vect}_k</m> have objects <m>k</m>-vector spaces and morphisms <m>k</m>-linear
          transformations. Since linear transformations compose (in the set-theoretic sense) to give new linear transformations,
          <m>\mathsf{Vect}_k</m> is also a category. (It is obvious that the identity function <m>1_V:V\to V</m> is linear.)
          We can also consider the category <m>\mathsf{FinVect}_k</m> of finite-dimensional <m>k</m>-vector spaces and <m>k</m>-linear
          transformations.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-empty-category">
      <title>The empty category</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>empty category</term> <m>\varnothing</m> has no objects (i.e. <m>\mathrm{Ob}\,\varnothing=\varnothing</m>) and no morphisms
          (<m>\mathrm{Mor}\,\varnothing=\varnothing</m>). The source, target, and composition functions are all the empty function
          <m>\varnothing\to\varnothing</m> and all properties are satisfied vacuously!
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-trivial-category">
      <title>The trivial category</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>trivial category</term> <m>\bullet</m> has a singleton set <m>\{*\}</m> for its objects and a single morphism
          (necessarily the identity on <m>*</m>), <m>\operatorname{id}_*:* \to *</m>. The only composition to define is 
          <m>\operatorname{id}_*\circ \operatorname{id}_*=\operatorname{id}_*</m> and this is enough
          to check the associativity and identity properties as well.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-mat">
      <title>A category whose morphisms are not functions</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Not every category has special classes of functions as morphisms. Consider <m>\mathsf{Mat}_k</m> whose objects are the natural numbers
          <m>\mathbb{N}=\{0,1,2,\ldots\}</m> and whose morphisms <m>\mathsf{Mat}_k(m,n)</m> are <m>n\times m</m> matrices with entries in a field
          <m>k</m>. Composition is given by matrix multiplication (check compatibility!) and <m>\operatorname{id}_k</m> is the <m>k\times k</m> 
          identity matrix. 
          Since matrix multiplication is associative, this forms a category.
        </p>

        <p>
          If you are suspicious that this category is eerily similar to <m>\mathsf{FinVect}_k</m>, worry not: it is! After studying equivalences of
          categories and skeleta, you will understand exactly how similar.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      The following two examples should seem completely obvious if you have already taken a course in abstract algebra. If you have not, there is no harm
      in skipping them.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="eg-groups">
      <title>Categories of groups</title>
      
      
      <statement>
        <p>
          There are categories <m>\mathsf{Gp}</m>, <m>\mathsf{FinGp}</m>, and <m>\mathsf{AbGp}</m> of groups, finite groups, and Abelian groups,
          respectively. In each case, morphisms are group homomorphisms.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-rings">
      <title>Categories of rings</title>
      
      
      <statement>
        <p>
          There are categories <m>\mathsf{Ring}</m> and <m>\mathsf{CommRing}</m> of rings and commutative rings, respectively. In both cases,
          morphisms are ring homomorphisms. There is also a category <m>\mathsf{Field}</m> of fields and field homomorphisms.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      Finally, we come to the category of primary interest in this course, the category of topological spaces and continuous functions.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="eg-top">
      <title>The category of topological spaces and continuous functions</title>
      
      
      <statement>
        <p>
          The category <m>\mathsf{Top}</m> has topological spaces as its objects and continuous functions as its morphisms. In order to check this, we must
          see that the composition of continuous functions is continuous and that identity functions are continuous. If <m>X</m> is a topological space and
          <m>\operatorname{id}_X:X\to X</m> is the identity function, then for any <m>U\subseteq X</m> open, <m>\operatorname{id}_X^{-1}(U)=U</m> is open in 
          <m>X</m>, so <m>\operatorname{id}\operatorname{id}_X</m> is continuous. The associativity and identity axioms hold because they hold for functions.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <remark xml:id="rmk-wrong-morphisms">
      <title>Choice of morphisms</title>
      <p>
        Of course, there is also a category whose objects are topological spaces and morphisms are arbitrary functions between underlying sets. And while we are
        free to define such a category, it is not of particular interest. A category is a tool for studying relationships between objects. If we choose the wrong
        set of relationships (i.e. the wrong morphisms), then we end up with an uninteresting — or, worse yet, misleading — category.
      </p>
    </remark>
    </subsubsection>
      <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-functors">
      <title>Functors</title>
      <p>
        If category theory is all about relations between mathematical objects, and categories are themselves mathematical objects 
        then we need a way to compare — or relate — categories. This is what functors do.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-functor">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <term>functor</term> from a category <m>\mathsf C</m> to a category <m>\mathsf D</m>, denoted 
            <m>F\colon \mathsf C\to \mathsf D</m> is an assignment on objects 
            <m>F\colon \operatorname{Ob} \mathsf C\to \operatorname{Ob} \mathsf D</m> together with an assignment on morphisms 
            <m>F\colon \mathsf C(x,y)\to \mathsf D(Fx,Fy)</m> for each <m>x,y\in \operatorname{Ob} \mathsf C</m> satisfying the 
            following properties:
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  for all <m>x\in\operatorname{Ob} \mathsf C</m>, <m>F\operatorname{id}_x = \operatorname{id}_{Fx}</m>, and
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  for every pair of composable morphisms <m>f\in \mathsf C(x,y)</m>, <m>g\in \mathsf C(y,z)</m>,
                  <md>
                    F(gf) = (Fg)(Ff).
                  </md>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <example>
        <title>The direct image functor</title>
        <p>
          There are multiple functors associated with the power set construction <m>X\mapsto 2^X</m>. Our first example is 
          direct image, which takes <m>X\mapsto 2^X</m> and <m>(f\colon X\to Y)\mapsto (f\colon 2^X\to 2^Y,~A\mapsto f[A]</m>. 
          You should check that the identity function maps to the identity on power sets, and that direct image commutes with 
          composition, <ie />, <m>(g\circ f)[A] = g[f[A]]</m>.
        </p>
      </example>
      
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>


  <subsection>
    <title>Wednesday</title>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-more-functors">
      <title>More on functors</title>
            <p>
        Some functors "reverse arrows". For instance, preimages famously satisfy <m>(g\circ f)^{-1} = f^{-1}\circ g^{-1}</m>. To 
        handle this formally, we make the following definition.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-opposite-cat">
        <title>Opposite category</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Given a category <m>\mathsf C</m>, its <term>opposite category</term> <m>\mathsf C^{\mathrm{op}}</m> has the same objects 
            as <m>\mathsf C</m> and <m>\mathsf C^{\mathrm{op}}(x,y) = \mathsf C(y,x)</m>. Composition in <m>\mathsf C^{\mathrm{op}}</m> 
            is given by composing in the swapped order in <m>\mathsf C</m>, and identities are the same as in <m>\mathsf C</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <exercise>        
        <p>
          Verify that <m>\mathsf C^{\mathrm{op}}</m> is a category.
        </p>
      </exercise>
      <p>
        A functor that "reverses arrows" can now be encoded as a functor <m>\mathsf C^{\mathrm{op}}\to \mathsf D</m>. Some authors call 
        this a <term>contravariant functor</term> <m>\mathsf C\to \mathsf D</m>, but we will try to avoid this language here.
      </p>
      <example>
        <title>The preimage functor</title>
        <p>
          The power set construction on objects also admits preimage as its functorial assignment on morphisms. That is, there is a functor 
          <m>\mathsf{Set}^{\mathrm{op}}\to \mathsf{Set}</m> given by
          <md>
            <mrow>X \amp \longmapsto 2^X</mrow>
            <mrow>(f\colon X\to Y) \amp \longmapsto (f^{-1}\colon 2^Y\to 2^X,~B\mapsto f^{-1}B := \{x\in X\mid f(x)\in B\}.</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </example>
      <p>
        Functors are fantastic tools. One thing you can do with them is prove existence results like the Brouwer fixed-point theorem. A 
        <term>fixed point</term> of a function <m>f\colon X\to X</m> is a point <m>x\in X</m> for which <m>f(x)=x</m>.
      </p>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-brouwer-fp">
        <title>Brouwer fixed-point theorem</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>D^n := \{x\in \mathbb R^n\mid \lVert x\rVert \le 1\}</m> denote the closed unit disk in Euclidean <m>n</m>-space for 
            some <m>n\ge 0</m>. Then every continuous function <m>D^n\to D^n</m> has a fixed point.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>f\colon D^n\to D^n</m> be a continuous function and suppose for contradiction that <m>f</m> does not admit a fixed 
          point. Then there is a well-defined continuous function <m>g\colon D^n \to S^{n-1} </m> taking <m>x</m> to the 
          unique point on <m>S^{n-1}</m> through which the ray from <m>f(x)</m> to <m>x</m> passes. (Can you prove that this is 
          continuous?) Since it will be important momentarily, 
          note that the restriction of <m>g</m> to <m>S^{n-1}\subseteq D^n</m> is the identity map.
        </p>
        <p>
          Later, we will introduce a functor called <term>homology</term>. The <m>k</m>-th homology functor
          <md>
            H_k\colon \mathsf{Top}\longrightarrow \mathsf{Ab}
          </md>
          from spaces to Abelian groups has something to do with "<m>k</m>-dimensional holes" and, in particular, we will compute
          <md>
            H_{n-1}S^{n-1}\cong \mathbb Z\qquad\text{and}\qquad H_{n-1}D^n = 0.
          </md>
          Since the restriction of <m>g</m> to <m>S^{n-1}</m> is the identity, we know that the diagram
          <image width="45%">
            <description>
              A commutative diagram with <m>S^{n-1}</m> at upper left and upper right, and <m>D^n</m> at the bottom.
              Arrows: <m>\operatorname{id}</m> from the left <m>S^{n-1}</m> to the right <m>S^{n-1}</m>;
              <m>\operatorname{inc}</m> from the left <m>S^{n-1}</m> down to <m>D^n</m>;
              and <m>g</m> from <m>D^n</m> up to the right <m>S^{n-1}</m>.
            </description>

            <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="cbrouwer">
              <diagram dimensions="(320,230)" margins="5">
                <coordinates bbox="(-1.6,-0.35,1.6,1.35)">

                  <definition>graph={0:[1,2], 1:[2]}</definition>

                  <network directed="yes" arrows="end"
                          graph="graph"
                          labels="yes"
                          node-style="circle"
                          node-fill="white" node-stroke="none"
                          node-size="44">

                    <node at="0" p="(-1,1.0)"><m>S^{n-1}</m></node>
                    <node at="1" p="(0,0.0)"><m>D^n</m></node>
                    <node at="2" p="(1,1.0)"><m>S^{n-1}</m></node>

                    <edge vertices="(0,2)" label-location="0.50" alignment="n"><m>\operatorname{id}</m></edge>
                    <edge vertices="(0,1)" label-location="0.50" alignment="sw"><m>\operatorname{inc}</m></edge>
                    <edge vertices="(1,2)" label-location="0.50" alignment="se"><m>g</m></edge>

                  </network>
                </coordinates>
              </diagram>
            </prefigure>
          </image>
          commutes. Applying <m>H_{n-1}</m>, it follows that the diagram
          <image width="45%">
            <description>
              A commutative diagram with <m>H_{n-1}S^{n-1}</m> at upper left and upper right, and <m>0</m> at the bottom.
              Arrows: <m>\operatorname{id}</m> from the left <m>H_{n-1}S^{n-1}</m> to the right <m>H_{n-1}S^{n-1}</m>;
              <m>H_{n-1}\operatorname{inc}</m> from the left <m>H_{n-1}S^{n-1}</m> down to <m>0</m>;
              and <m>H_{n-1}g</m> from <m>0</m> up to the right <m>H_{n-1}S^{n-1}</m>.
            </description>

            <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="homology-brouwer">
              <diagram dimensions="(320,230)" margins="5">
                <coordinates bbox="(-1.6,-0.35,1.6,1.35)">

                  <definition>graph={0:[1,2], 1:[2]}</definition>

                  <network directed="yes" arrows="end"
                          graph="graph"
                          labels="yes"
                          node-style="circle"
                          node-fill="white" node-stroke="none"
                          node-size="44">

                    <node at="0" p="(-1,1.0)"><m>H_{n-1}S^{n-1}</m></node>
                    <node at="1" p="(0,0.0)"><m>0</m></node>
                    <node at="2" p="(1,1.0)"><m>H_{n-1}S^{n-1}</m></node>

                    <edge vertices="(0,2)" label-location="0.50" alignment="n"><m>\operatorname{id}</m></edge>
                    <edge vertices="(0,1)" label-location="0.50" alignment="sw"><m>H_{n-1}\operatorname{inc}</m></edge>
                    <edge vertices="(1,2)" label-location="0.50" alignment="se"><m>H_{n-1}g</m></edge>

                  </network>
                </coordinates>
              </diagram>
            </prefigure>
          </image>
          commutes. This is a contradiction since the identity map between nonzero Abelian groups does not factor through the 
          trivial group! We conclude that a fixed point must exist after all.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-new-from-old">
      <title>New topologies from old</title>
      <p>
        We now undertake the construction of new topological spaces from old ones, with a focus on the subspace, product, coproduct, 
        and quotient topologies. Later, we will also talk about function spaces.
      </p>
      <p>
        In each case, we employ the following pattern in developing our intuition:
        <dl>
          <li>
            <title>Universal property</title>
            <p>
              Say what we want the space to do in a way that specifies the construction up to unique homeomorphism.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <title>Construction</title>
            <p>
              Provide a concrete desciption of the space and verify that it satisfies the universal property.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <title>Examples</title>
            <p>
              Get familiar with the space, universal property, and construction by playing with well-chosen examples.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <title>Other contexts</title>
            <p>
              By stating the universal property of our <m>\mathsf{Top}</m>-situated construction in other categories, we 
              can deepen our understanding and build bridges between topology and other parts of mathematics.
            </p>
          </li>
        </dl>
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-subspace">
      <title>The subspace topology</title>
      <p>
        Given a space <m>X</m> and subset <m>A\subseteq X</m>, we have already defined the <term>subspace topology</term> on <m>A</m>. It 
        has open sets of the form <m>A\cap U</m> where <m>U\subseteq X</m> is open.
      </p>
      <p>
        But <alert>why</alert> did we make this definition? What does the subspace topology on <m>A</m> do for us that other topologies 
        do not?
      </p>
      <p>
        To answer this question, we will extend our notion of "subspace" a bit and develop its <alert>universal property</alert> in 
        categorical language.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-subspace-top">
        <title>Subspace topology by universal property</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose <m>X</m> is a space, <m>A</m> is a set, and <m>i\colon A\to X</m> is an injective function. Then the 
            <term>subspace topology</term> on <m>A</m> (relative to <m>i</m>) is the topology satisfying the 
            following universal property:
            <blockquote>
              <p>
                <m>i\colon A\to X</m> is continuous and for any space <m>K</m> and function <m>f\colon K\to A</m>, the map 
                <m>f</m> is continuous if and only if <m>i\circ f\colon K\to X</m> is continuous.
              </p>
            </blockquote>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        We now need to check that this universal property characterizes the subspace topology.
      </p>
      <proposition xml:id="prop-subspace-up">
        <statement>
          <title>Characterizing the subspace topology</title>
          <p>
            Suppose <m>X</m> is a space, <m>A</m> is a set, and <m>i\colon A\to X</m> is an injective function. 
            If <m>(A,\tau)</m> and <m>(A,\tau')</m> are topologies on <m>A</m> satisfying the condition of <xref ref="def-subspace-top" />, 
            then <m>\tau=\tau'</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Take <m>K = (A,\tau')</m> and <m>f=\operatorname{id}\colon A\to A</m>. Since <m>i\circ f=i</m>, the universal property 
          of <m>(A,\tau)</m> implies that <m>\operatorname{id}\colon (A,\tau')\to (A,\tau)</m> is continuous. 
          The analogous argument with <m>K = (A,\tau)</m> invoking the universal property of <m>(A,\tau')</m> implies that 
          <m>\operatorname{id}\colon (A,\tau)\to (A,\tau')</m> is continuous. We conclude that 
          <m>\operatorname{id}\colon (A,\tau)\to (A,\tau')</m> is a homeomorphism. The reader may check that the identity map is 
          a homeomorphism if and only if <m>\tau=\tau'</m>.
        </p>

      </proof>
      <p>
        The above proposition is critical for checking that <alert>at most one</alert> topology on <m>A</m> is a subspace 
        topology on <m>A</m>. But more is needed — we must also know that <alert>at least one</alert> subspace topology on <m>A</m> 
        exists!
      </p>
      <proposition xml:id="prop-subspace-construction">
        <title>Constructing the subspace topology</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose <m>X</m> is a space, <m>A</m> is a set, and <m>i\colon A\to X</m> is an injective function. Define
            <md>
              \tau_{\text{sub}} := \{i^{-1}U\mid U\subseteq X\text{ open}\}.
            </md>
            Then <m>(A,\tau_{\text{sub}})</m> satisfies the universal property of <xref ref="def-subspace-top" />.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>
      <exercise>
        <title>The subspace topology is a topology</title>
        <p>
          Verify that <m>\tau_{\text{sub}}</m> is a topology on <m>A</m>.
        </p>
      </exercise>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Endow <m>A</m> with the topology <m>\tau_{\text{sub}}</m>. Fix a space <m>K</m> and function <m>f\colon K\to A</m>. 
          For the forwards implication, suppose that <m>f</m> is continuous. We need to check that <m>i\circ f</m> is continuous. 
          Since continuity is preserved by composition, it suffices to prove that <m>i\colon A\to X</m> is continuous with respect 
          to <m>\tau_{\text{sub}}</m>. This follows immediately from the definitions of continuity and <m>\tau_{\text{sub}}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          For the backwards implication, suppose that <m>i\circ f\colon K\to X</m> is continuous (without assuming <m>f</m> is continuous). 
          Suppose <m>V\in \tau_{\text{sub}}</m>. Then <m>V = i^{-1}U</m> for some <m>U\subseteq X</m> open. We observe that
          <md>
            f^{-1}V = f^{-1}[i^{-1}[U]] = (i\circ f)^{-1}U.
          </md>
          Since <m>i\circ f</m> is continuous, we know that this is an open subset of <m>K</m>. This verifies that <m>f</m> is continuous, 
          as desired.
        </p>
      </proof>
      <p>
        We are now justified in talking about <alert>the</alert> subspace topology on <m>A</m> 
        (relative to the injection <m>i\colon A\to X</m>). We have already seen a number of examples of subspaces, so we only provide one 
        new one here.
      </p>
      <example>
        <title>A non-discrete countable subspace of <m>\mathbb R</m> in which all but one point is isolated</title>
        <p>
          Consider the set <m>A:= \{0\}\cup \{1/n\mid n\in \mathbb Z_{\gt 0}\}\subseteq \mathbb R</m> with the subspace topology. 
          Despite being in natural bijection with the discrete subspace <m>\mathbb N\subseteq \mathbb R</m>, it is <alert>not</alert> 
          the case that <m>A</m> is discrete. Indeed, every open subset of <m>A</m> containing <m>0</m> contains other elements of 
          <m>A</m> as well, whereas every point of <m>\mathbb N</m> is <term>isolated</term> — its associated singleton subset is open. 
          You should check that every nonzero element of <m>A</m> is isolated.
        </p>
      </example>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>


  <subsection>
    <title>Friday</title>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-quotient">
      <title>The quotient topology</title>
    <p>
      Quotients are ubiquitous, and you are already familiar with some important examples. For instance, modular arithmetic passes 
      from the integers <m>\mathbb Z</m> to the integers mod <m>n</m>, <m>\mathbb Z/n\mathbb Z</m>. The elements of the latter are 
      equivalence classes of the form <m>x+n\mathbb Z</m> for <m>x\in \mathbb Z</m>. Of course, there are only <m>n</m> such 
      equivalence classes since <m>x+n\mathbb Z=y+n\mathbb Z</m> if and only if <m>x-y\in n\mathbb Z</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      This motivating example is not so interesting topologically since we usually view <m>\mathbb Z</m> as a discrete space. But here 
      is a related construction: for real numbers <m>x,y</m>, declare <m>x\sim y</m> if and only if <m>x-y\in \mathbb Z</m>. We will call 
      this quotient <m>\mathbb R/\mathbb Z</m>.
    </p>
    <exercise>
      <title>Guess the topology of <m>\mathbb R/\mathbb Z</m></title>
      <p>
        How can you visualize <m>\mathbb R/\mathbb Z</m>? Is there a familiar space to which it "should" be homeomorphic?
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      Here's another case in which a topology on quotients would be useful. The idea is that we would like a space whose points parametrize 
      lines through the origin in <m>\mathbb R^{n+1}</m>. As a first attempt, we might imagine an equivalence relation on 
      <m>\mathbb R^{n+1}</m> where <m>x\sim y</m> if and only if <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are on the same line through the origin. This 
      immediately hits a snag since every line through the origin contains the origin, so <m>x\sim 0\sim y</m> for all 
      <m>x,y\in\mathbb R^{n+1}</m> and we have collapsed everything into the same equivalence class. But there is an easy fix: first remove 
      the origin from <m>\mathbb R^{n+1}</m>, and then declare <m>x\sim y</m> :iff <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are on the same line through the 
      origin. Equivalently, <m>x\sim y</m> if and only if <m>x=\lambda y</m> for some 
      <m>\lambda\in \mathbb R^\times = \mathbb R\smallsetminus \{0\}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      We write <m>\mathbb{RP}^n := (\mathbb R^{n+1}\smallsetminus \{0\})/\sim</m> and call this space 
      <term>real projective <m>n</m>-space</term>. But we haven't pinned down the topology yet! The "collapsing" occuring in the quotient 
      is far more dramatic here, and it is less clear what the resulting space "looks like".
    </p>
    <exercise>
      <title>Guess the topologies of <m>\mathbb{RP}^1</m> and <m>\mathbb{RP}^2</m>.</title>
      <p>
        The homeomorphism type of <m>\mathbb{RP}^1</m> is one you've encountered before. Can you see it? What about <m>\mathbb{RP}^2</m>?
      </p>
    </exercise>
    With this motivation in mind, we now develop the quotient topology, following our usual pattern of universal property, 
    construction, examples, and other contexts. All our constructions will be predicated upon a surjective function <m>q\colon X\to Z</m>, 
    but the reader is invited to imagine <m>Z=X/\sim</m> where <m>x\sim x'</m> :iff <m>q(x)=q(x')</m>. 
    <definition xml:id="def-quotient-top">
      <title>Quotient topology by universal property</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>X</m> be a space and let <m>q\colon X\to Z</m> be a surjective function. The <term>quotient topology</term> on <m>Z</m> 
          satisfies the following universal property:
          <blockquote>
            <p>
              the map <m>q\colon X\to Z</m> is continuous and, for any space <m>K</m>, a function <m>f\colon Z\to K</m> is continuous 
              if and only if the composite <m>f\circ q\colon X\to Z\to K</m> is continuous.
            </p>
          </blockquote>
          In this case, we call <m>q\colon X\to Z</m> a <term>quotient map</term>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      Our next task is to check that the universal property characterizes the quotient topology.
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="prop-quotient-unique">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>(Z,\tau)</m> and <m>(Z,\tau')</m> are topologies on <m>Z</m> satisfying the universal property of 
          <xref ref="def-quotient-top" />, then <m>\tau=\tau'</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </proposition>
    <proof>
      <p>
        This will be part of your homework!
      </p>
    </proof>
    <p>
      In many practical situations, we will have a quotient map <m>q\colon X\to Z</m> at hand, and also a continuous function 
      <m>f\colon X\to Y</m>, and we will want to know whether <m>f</m> <term>extends</term> along <m>q</m>. That is, is there a 
      continuous function <m>\tilde f\colon Z\to Y</m> such that <m>\tilde f\circ q=f</m>? This is best split up into a set theoretic 
      and topological component.
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="prop-func-preserve-fibers">
      <title>Fiber-preserving functions factor through the quotient</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>q\colon X\to Z</m> is a surjective function and <m>f\colon X\to Y</m> is some other function. Then <m>f</m> 
          <term>factors through</term> <m>Z</m> (via <m>q</m>) — that is, there exists <m>\tilde f\colon Z\to Y</m> such that 
          <m>f=\tilde f \circ q</m> — if and only if <m>f</m> is constant on the fibers of <m>q</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </proposition>
    <aside>
      <title>Fibers</title>
      <p>
        A <term>fiber</term> of <m>q\colon X\to Z</m> is defined to be the preimage of a singleton subset of <m>Z</m>. To say that 
        <m>f</m> is constant on the fibers of <m>q</m> is to say that <m>q(x)=q(x')</m> implies <m>f(x)=f(x')</m>. When <m>q</m> is the 
        canonical quotient <m>X\to X/\sim</m>, this condition says that <m>x\sim x'</m> implies <m>f(x)=f(x')</m>, <ie /> <m>f</m> respects 
        <m>\sim</m>.
      </p>
    </aside>
    <proof>
      <p>
        The reader should verify this statement for themselves!
      </p>
    </proof>
    <p>
      By combining <xref ref="def-quotient-top" /> and <xref ref="prop-func-preserve-fibers" />, we immediately arrive at the following:
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="prop-top-factor-quotient">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>q\colon X\to Z</m> is a quotient map in <m>\mathsf{Top}</m> and <m>f\colon X\to Y</m> is a continuous function. Then 
          <m>f</m> admits a continuous factorization through <m>Z</m> if and only if <m>f</m> is constant on the fibers of <m>q</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </proposition>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Since <m>f</m> is constant on fibers, <xref ref="prop-func-preserve-fibers" /> provides a function 
        <m>\tilde f\colon Z\to Y</m> such that <m>f=\tilde f\circ q</m>. Now <xref ref="def-quotient-top" /> kicks in and tells us that 
        <m>\tilde f</m> is continuous because <m>f</m> is.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <p>
      It is now time to ensure that quotient topologies exist.
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="prop-quotient-construction">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>X</m> be a space and let <m>q\colon X\to Z</m> be a surjective function. Then the topology
          <md>
            \tau_{\text{quot}} := \{V\subseteq Z\mid q^{-1}V\subseteq X\text{ open}\}
          </md>
          satisfies the conditions of <xref ref="def-quotient-top" /> and makes <m>q</m> a quotient map.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </proposition>
    <proof>
      <p>
        First observe that <m>q\colon X\to (Z,\tau_{\text{quot}})</m> is continuous by definition of <m>\tau_{\text{quot}}</m>. We now need 
        to show that for a space <m>K</m> and function <m>f\colon Z\to K</m>, <m>f</m> is continuous if and only if <m>f\circ q</m> is continuous. 
        The forwards direction is automatic since composition preserves continuity. For the backwards direction, suppose <m>f\circ q</m> is 
        continuous. Given <m>U\subseteq K</m> open, we need to guarantee that <m>f^{-1}U\subseteq Z</m> is open in <m>Z</m>. 
        By definition of <m>\tau_{\text{quot}}</m>, this is the case if and only if <m>q^{-1}[f^{-1}U]\subseteq X</m> is open. But of course 
        <m>q^{-1}[f^{-1}U]\subseteq X = (f\circ q)^{-1}U</m>, and the latter is open by continuity of <m>f\circ q</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
    </subsubsection>
    <p>
      Now that we know that there is a unique quotient topology satisfying <xref ref="def-quotient-top" />, we are ready to explore some 
      examples in-depth.
    </p>
    <example>
      <title><m>\mathbb R/\mathbb Z</m> is a circle</title>
      <p>
        The map <m>f\colon \mathbb R\to S^1</m> given by <m>f(t) = e^{2\pi i t}</m> is continuous and constant on the fibers of the 
        quotient map <m>q\colon \mathbb R\to \mathbb R/\mathbb Z</m>, thus there is a continuous map 
        <m>\tilde f\colon \mathbb R/\mathbb Z\to S^1</m> such that <m>f=\tilde f\circ q</m>. The reader may check that <m>\tilde f</m> 
        is a bijection (straightforward) and an open map (more work) and thus <m>\tilde f\colon \mathbb R/\mathbb Z\cong S^1</m>.
      </p>
    </example>
    <example>
      <title><m>\mathbb{RP}^1</m> is a circle</title>
      <p>
        This is a similar argument to the previous example, but using <m>f\colon \mathbb R^2\smallsetminus \{0\}\to S^1</m> defined by 
        <md>
          f(x) = \frac x{\lVert x\rVert}.
        </md>
      </p>
    </example>
    <example>
      <title>The topology of <m>\mathbb{RP}^2</m></title>
      <p>
        The lines 
      </p>
    </example>
    <example>
      <title>The space of unit cubes</title>
      <p>
        
      </p>
      
    </example>
  </subsection>
</section>
